"""
MKT Context Commentary — Job chapters 1–4
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-job-1-4.py

Ch 1 (v2-22): ANE setting — the land of Uz (Edom/trans-Jordan); the divine council
    in Ugaritic and Mesopotamian cosmology; ha-Satan as court adversary (cf. Zech 3);
    Ludlul bel nemeqi (Babylonian Job) and the "disinterested piety" question;
    the Sabeans and Chaldeans as attested historical groups; mourning customs.
Ch 2: The skin disease in ancient medicine; the ash-heap as social location;
    the three friends — Teman/Shuah/Naamah in ANE geography and wisdom traditions;
    the seven-day mourning period.
Ch 3: The birthday-curse genre (Jer 20:14-18 parallel); the Leviathan myth in Ugaritic
    texts (Baal and Yam cycle, Lotan); Sheol as ANE underworld; the lament genre.
Ch 4: Teman as a center of Edomite wisdom; the retributive justice principle in
    Mesopotamian wisdom (Babylonian Theodicy); the nocturnal vision and ANE
    dream-incubation; the divine council hierarchy in ancient cosmology.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "1": {
    "2": "<p>The patriarchal family structure &mdash; seven sons and three daughters &mdash; uses the schematic numbers of completeness: seven signals fullness (the complete week; seven-branch menorah; seven-day feasts), while three is a secondary number of completion. Large families were the OT&rsquo;s primary indicator of divine blessing (Ps 127:3&ndash;5; 128:3), and the loss of all ten children at once would be recognized as a catastrophe of cosmological proportions within the ANE value system where children = wealth = divine favor.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Job&rsquo;s livestock inventory places him in the trading world of the Syrian desert steppe. Camels (<em>gemallim</em>) were the primary long-distance trading animals of the Arabian peninsula and a major indicator of wealth in the patriarchal period (cf. Gen 12:16; 24:10 &mdash; Abraham&rsquo;s camels). The figure of 3,000 camels represents enormous wealth. The Sabeans and Chaldeans (vv15,17) who raid this wealth were attested real-world groups: the Sabeans (South Arabian traders, associated with Sheba in southern Arabia/Yemen), the Chaldeans (the Aramaean groups from the Euphrates region who became the core of the Neo-Babylonian empire). Job&rsquo;s identification as &ldquo;the greatest man among all the people of the East&rdquo; places him at the pinnacle of the trans-Arabian trading world.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The rotating feast cycle of the seven sons reflects the aristocratic household pattern of the ancient Levant: extended family obligations required periodic hospitality. The detail that they invited their three sisters is significant socially &mdash; adult daughters of a great household were included in the family&rsquo;s festivities, which reflects a higher-status household structure than the typical patriarchal arrangement. The feast cycle created a predictable rhythm, which is precisely what made the catastrophic disruption of v13&ndash;19 so devastating.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Job&rsquo;s regular pre-dawn intercession and burnt offerings (<em>&rsquo;olot</em>) for each of his children reflects the patriarchal-period pattern of the household head functioning as a priest for his family (cf. Noah in Gen 8:20; Abraham in Gen 22:2; Isaac in Gen 26:25). Before the Levitical priesthood was institutionalized, the <em>paterfamilias</em> offered sacrifice. The concern about his children having &ldquo;blessed God in their hearts&rdquo; reflects the ancient understanding that sin of thought (not only deed) required atoning sacrifice &mdash; a more refined moral theology than many ancient Near Eastern legal codes, which focused on outward acts.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The <strong>divine council</strong> (<em>bene ha-&rsquo;elohim</em>, sons of God) presenting before YHWH has close parallels in ancient Ugaritic literature from Ras Shamra (ancient Ugarit, 14th&ndash;12th century BCE). The Ugaritic texts describe El presiding over an assembly of gods at the &ldquo;mount of assembly&rdquo; (<em>phr m&rsquo;d</em>). In Mesopotamian cosmology, the assembly of the great gods (<em>puhur ilani</em>) met to determine human fates. The OT adapts this imagery: YHWH holds court with his divine servants (<em>bene ha-&rsquo;elohim</em>), but the model is that of a king with his courtiers rather than a pantheon of equal gods. Ps 82 and 1 Kgs 22:19&ndash;22 use the same divine-council scene.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The adversary&rsquo;s description of roaming the earth mirrors the divine reconnaissance missions in Zech 1:10&ndash;11 (horsemen who patrol the earth) and 6:7. In the ancient court system, the king would send out agents to observe and report on conditions throughout the realm; the adversary functions as such an agent who has been on a patrol mission and reports back to the divine king. The concept of a divine intelligence-gathering network is also reflected in Prov 15:3: &ldquo;the eyes of YHWH are in every place, watching the evil and the good.&rdquo;</p>",
    "8": "<p>YHWH&rsquo;s initiative in calling the adversary&rsquo;s attention to Job reflects a concept deeply embedded in ANE thought: the gods took a special interest in certain individuals they favored, and this interest could itself become the occasion for testing. The <em>Ludlul bel nemeqi</em> (&ldquo;I Will Praise the Lord of Wisdom,&rdquo; a Babylonian composition sometimes called the &ldquo;Babylonian Job&rdquo;) begins with a nobleman who enjoyed divine favor until he was suddenly abandoned by his divine protectors. The four-descriptor portrait of Job (blameless, upright, fearing God, turning from evil) is YHWH&rsquo;s own assessment &mdash; the creator vouching for his creature&rsquo;s integrity.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The adversary&rsquo;s central question &mdash; &ldquo;Does Job fear God for nothing?&rdquo; &mdash; reflects a sophisticated skepticism about human motivation that has parallels in ancient wisdom literature. The <em>Babylonian Theodicy</em> (ca. 1000 BCE) includes a dialogue between a sufferer and a friend in which the friend cynically argues that humans only appear righteous for self-interested reasons. The adversary&rsquo;s claim is precisely this: piety is always instrumental. The book of Job is structured as the divine experiment to test whether disinterested piety (fearing God simply for who God is, not for what he gives) is possible for a human being.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The protective &ldquo;fence&rdquo; around Job describes a common ANE belief that each person had divine protectors who surrounded them. Mesopotamian religion included the concept of personal gods (<em>ilu</em> and <em>ishtaru</em>) who guarded and guided individuals; a person who suffered might be understood as having lost divine protection. The adversary claims that Job&rsquo;s piety is a rational response to divine generosity and protection, not genuine devotion. The word for &ldquo;blessed the work of his hands&rdquo; uses the same <em>barakh</em> verb that will appear as the euphemism for &ldquo;curse&rdquo; throughout the prologue (vv5, 11; 2:5, 9) &mdash; an ironic lexical echo.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The adversary&rsquo;s challenge functions as a formal legal proposition in the divine court: if you strike Job&rsquo;s possessions, he will curse you. In ancient Near Eastern legal and administrative contexts, a wager or challenge of this kind carried formal weight when made before witnesses. The divine council serves as the witness body for the adversary&rsquo;s challenge, making the test a formally witnessed cosmic experiment. The result &mdash; YHWH&rsquo;s permission to proceed &mdash; is thus the divine acceptance of the challenge terms.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The permission structure in the divine council &mdash; &ldquo;all he has is in your power; only do not lay a hand on the man himself&rdquo; &mdash; reflects the ancient understanding of bounded divine permission. In Mesopotamian theology, the divine assembly determined human fates at the New Year festival; an individual&rsquo;s fate could be altered by decision of the divine council. YHWH&rsquo;s limitation on the adversary&rsquo;s scope reflects his sovereignty: the test proceeds under defined parameters, not in an open-ended framework of adversarial power.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The setting of the catastrophe &mdash; the sons and daughters feasting at the oldest brother&rsquo;s house &mdash; is the household feast cycle of v4. Ancient feasting practices in the Levant involved significant quantities of wine (&ldquo;eating and drinking wine&rdquo;), shared family celebration, and the rotation of hospitality among siblings. The detail that it was the <em>bekhorah</em> (firstborn&rsquo;s) house creates a cyclical completion: the feast cycle has reached the eldest, and it is on this occasion that disaster falls.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The Sabeans (<em>Sheva</em>) were a South Arabian trading people centered in the modern Yemen-Oman region; their queen visited Solomon (1 Kgs 10:1), and they appear in Ps 72:10 as a distant tribute-paying nation. As semi-nomadic raiders, they were known to descend on settled wealth in trans-Jordan and northern Arabia. The attack on oxen plowing (agricultural work) and donkeys grazing represents the destruction of the economic foundation of an agrarian household.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The structure of the four catastrophes (vv14&ndash;19) is carefully constructed for maximum dramatic effect through overlapping narration. Each messenger arrives while the previous is still speaking, creating a cascade of disaster without pause for processing. Ancient Near Eastern narratives occasionally use similar cascade structures for dramatic catastrophe (the successive plagues of Exodus move in a similar building pattern), but the overlapping messenger device in Job is unusually precise and deliberate in its literary design.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;Fire from God&rdquo; (<em>&rsquo;esh &rsquo;elohim</em>) is a phrase associated with lightning in the OT (cf. 2 Kgs 1:12 where fire falls from heaven; Num 11:1-3). In the ancient world, lightning was unambiguously a divine weapon: in Mesopotamian mythology, the storm-god Adad wielded lightning bolts; in Ugaritic mythology, Baal wielded the <em>barqu</em> (lightning). The attribution of fire to God is thus theologically loaded &mdash; God&rsquo;s own weapon appears to destroy Job&rsquo;s livestock and servants, which deepens the theological irony of the prologue: the divine permission has resulted in what appears to be a direct divine attack.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The Chaldeans (<em>Kasdim</em>) were the Aramaean tribal group from the lower Euphrates region who founded the Neo-Babylonian dynasty (ca. 626&ndash;539 BCE). Their appearance in the prologue alongside the Sabeans spans the two poles of the ancient Near East: south Arabia and Mesopotamia. In the story&rsquo;s historical setting, before the Babylonian empire&rsquo;s rise, the Chaldeans were raiders from the eastern steppe. Three raiding companies (<em>reshim shalosha</em>) reflects a standard military unit structure in ancient Near Eastern warfare.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The final disaster &mdash; the wind destroying the house during the eldest son&rsquo;s feast &mdash; brings the catastrophe back to the household feast of v4,13. The <em>eldest brother&rsquo;s house</em> as the location of the fatal wind is a narrative echo: the very feast cycle that Job carefully guarded with priestly intercession (v5) is the occasion of the final blow. The catastrophic death of all ten children in a single wind event would be understood in the ancient world as a divine stroke of overwhelming and inexplicable power.</p>",
    "19": "<p>A <em>ruah gedola</em> (great wind) striking the four corners of a house describes a building collapse caused by a violent desert wind &mdash; possibly a tornado or violent dust storm (<em>hamsin</em>/<em>sharav</em>) of the type common in the Levant in certain seasons. &ldquo;Four corners&rdquo; suggests the entire building was structurally compromised simultaneously, not merely one wall. In the ancient world, such an event would be read as unmistakably supernatural &mdash; a wind that surrounds and simultaneously strikes a building&rsquo;s four cardinal points.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Job&rsquo;s response follows the standard ANE mourning protocol precisely: tearing the outer garment (<em>me&rsquo;il</em>) and shaving the head are the classic signs of mourning (cf. Josh 7:6; Ezra 9:3; Isa 15:2; Jer 7:29). The shaving of the head was practiced across the ancient Near East as a mourning gesture: Ugaritic mourning texts, Mesopotamian lament literature, and Egyptian mourning customs all include head-shaving as a standard grief expression. Falling to the ground prostrate was simultaneously a mourning posture and a worship posture, which is precisely the ambiguity of Job&rsquo;s response &mdash; the five verbs of v20 contain both grief and worship inseparably.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The naked-at-birth / naked-at-death formula expresses a wisdom about material possessions that appears in various forms across ancient cultures: the Stoic tradition (particularly Marcus Aurelius and Epictetus), the Epicurean tradition, and Egyptian wisdom texts all contain similar reflections. Within the OT, Eccl 5:15 expresses the same idea. The specific formula &ldquo;YHWH gave, and YHWH has taken away&rdquo; is a theological condensation of Deuteronomic theology: YHWH is the source of all blessing, and his withdrawal of blessing is as sovereign an act as its giving. The doxology &mdash; &ldquo;blessed be the name of YHWH&rdquo; &mdash; was likely a liturgical formula used in formal worship contexts (cf. Ps 113:2).</p>",
    "22": "<p>The narrator&rsquo;s verdict &mdash; &ldquo;Job did not sin or accuse God of wrongdoing&rdquo; &mdash; is the divine court&rsquo;s equivalent of an acquittal. In ancient Near Eastern legal proceedings, the judgment of a case by its outcome (<em>ex eventu</em>) was standard: what happened after the court decision was the evidence of justice. The book&rsquo;s framing requires this authorial verdict to establish the legitimacy of the adversary&rsquo;s falsification: the test&rsquo;s first round is complete, and the adversary&rsquo;s hypothesis has been empirically refuted.</p>"
  },
  "2": {
    "1": "<p>The divine council reconvenes with identical staging to ch1: the <em>bene ha-&rsquo;elohim</em> assemble, the adversary comes among them. The formal repetition is a literary device that frames the second test as a structural parallel to the first &mdash; same setting, same participants, same challenge-and-permission format. Ancient Near Eastern divine council scenes in literature often use this kind of formal repetition to signal a parallel narrative sequence (e.g., the two Baal cycle tablets from Ugarit follow similar patterns in their two main combat episodes).</p>",
    "2": "<p>The adversary&rsquo;s identical response to YHWH&rsquo;s question (&ldquo;from roaming through the earth and walking back and forth on it&rdquo;) creates a deliberate verbatim repetition. Ancient Hebrew narrative uses exact repetition of dialogue as a formal literary device (cf. the messenger speeches in Genesis that repeat commands verbatim when delivered). The repetition here emphasizes the adversary&rsquo;s unchanged status and activity between the two scenes &mdash; he is still the earth-roaming patrol agent, still in the same relationship to the divine court.</p>",
    "3": "<p>YHWH&rsquo;s acknowledgment that the adversary &ldquo;incited me against him to ruin him without cause&rdquo; is a remarkable theological concession. In ancient Near Eastern divine court literature, a deity acknowledging agency in a morally complex action was unusual &mdash; divine actions were typically presented as simply sovereign and therefore justified. The book of Job pushes this boundary: YHWH explicitly acknowledges that the test was the adversary&rsquo;s instigation and that the destruction was causeless (<em>hinam</em>). This is a distinctive OT theological move that places divine sovereignty and divine goodness in genuine tension.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The &ldquo;skin for skin&rdquo; formula is a commercial or proverbial saying whose exact origins are unknown. In ancient trade contexts, the exchange rate of one commodity for another was expressed in such formulaic terms. Some interpreters read it as a reference to hide-trading: leather merchants bartering one type of skin for another, always keeping the calculation self-interested. The underlying anthropology is the adversary&rsquo;s consistent claim: humans are rational self-interested maximizers, and any apparent piety is a calculated exchange for divine protection or blessing.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The escalation from possessions to body reflects a graduated understanding of suffering in ancient thought: losing property was serious but survivable; bodily suffering attacks the person directly and cannot be escaped even in sleep or distraction. In Mesopotamian medicine and theology, skin diseases were understood as divine punishments (the Akkadian medical text <em>Sakikku</em> lists diseases and their divine causes). A severe, painful, visible skin disease in the ancient world also carried the social consequence of exclusion from community &mdash; as the following verses show, Job ends up outside the city on the ash-heap.</p>",
    "6": "<p>YHWH&rsquo;s second permission sets a new limit: the adversary may attack Job&rsquo;s body but must preserve his life (<em>nefesh</em>). The preservation of life as the inviolable boundary within the suffering permitted to the adversary is theologically significant: whatever suffering is permitted, it stops short of death. This corresponds to the general OT understanding that YHWH holds the keys of death and life (Deut 32:39: &ldquo;I kill and I make alive&rdquo;) and that this ultimate power is not delegated even to the adversary.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The disease <em>shehin ra&rsquo;</em> (severe inflammatory sores) has been identified by various commentators with conditions ranging from elephantiasis to smallpox to severe eczema. The Ugaritic cognate <em>shhn</em> appears in a list of diseases associated with Mot (death) in Ugaritic ritual texts. In ancient medicine, skin diseases of this type were treated with scraping (as v8 describes) to remove crusts and exudate. The disease&rsquo;s coverage &ldquo;from the sole of his foot to the top of his head&rdquo; is the merism of totality &mdash; expressing universal bodily affliction.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The <strong>ash-heap</strong> (<em>&rsquo;efer</em>) where Job sits was likely a public waste disposal site outside the settlement. In ancient Israelite and Canaanite towns, the ash-heap or refuse dump was located outside the city gates and served as the social location of those excluded from community life (cf. the poor sitting on the ash-heap in 1 Sam 2:8; Ps 113:7). Job&rsquo;s relocation to the ash-heap from his position as the city&rsquo;s most respected leader (29:7) represents a total social reversal: from the city gate (the place of honor and judgment) to the ash-heap (the place of refuse and outcasts).</p>",
    "9": "<p>Job&rsquo;s wife&rsquo;s counsel &mdash; &ldquo;curse God and die&rdquo; &mdash; has been interpreted both harshly (as Satanic temptation, as Augustine argued) and sympathetically (as the desperate suggestion of a woman who has also lost everything). In the ancient world, the wife of a <em>paterfamilias</em> had no independent legal standing; her social status was entirely dependent on her husband&rsquo;s position. She has lost her children, her household status, and now watches her husband suffer with no relief in sight. The LXX expands her speech considerably (adding a long lament), suggesting that later tradition recognized the pathos of her position and sought to give it fuller expression.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Job&rsquo;s rebuke &mdash; speaking &ldquo;as one of the foolish women&rdquo; &mdash; distinguishes between the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s sage (<em>hakham</em>) and the fool (<em>naval</em>). Nabal in 1 Samuel 25 is the paradigm case: a man whose name means &ldquo;fool&rdquo; and who acts accordingly, disregarding social obligation and divine order. The fool&rsquo;s speech is characterized in wisdom literature as acting as though there is no moral order in the universe (Ps 14:1: &ldquo;the fool says in his heart there is no God&rdquo; &mdash; not intellectual atheism but practical disregard for divine moral order). Job&rsquo;s response establishes that his wife&rsquo;s counsel falls into this category.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The three friends come from specific geographical and wisdom traditions. <strong>Eliphaz the Temanite</strong>: Teman was a region of Edom associated with legendary wisdom (Jer 49:7: &ldquo;Is wisdom no more in Teman? Has counsel perished from the prudent? Has their wisdom vanished?&rdquo;). Teman is also associated with the divine warrior march in Hab 3:3. <strong>Bildad the Shuhite</strong>: Shuah appears in Gen 25:2 as a son of Abraham and Keturah, placing him in the trans-Jordan / north Arabian region. <strong>Zophar the Naamathite</strong>: Naamah is uncertain; several locations in southern Canaan or Arabia have been proposed. All three represent the wisdom traditions of the non-Israelite peoples surrounding Israel.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The friends&rsquo; inability to recognize Job at a distance reflects the severity of his transformation. In the ancient world, recognition by sight was the primary social identification mechanism &mdash; a person&rsquo;s appearance communicated their status, health, and identity. Job&rsquo;s skin disease, ash-covered condition, and gaunt frame would make him unrecognizable as the person they knew. The three mourning gestures &mdash; weeping aloud, tearing garments, throwing dust skyward &mdash; are all attested mourning customs. The dust thrown toward heaven is an unusual gesture; it may express an appeal or protest directed toward God, expressing the mourners&rsquo; bewilderment at what they see.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The seven-day silent mourning is the standard full mourning period in the ancient world. In Mesopotamian practice, seven-day mourning for the dead was common (cf. the Gilgamesh epic: Gilgamesh mourns Enkidu for seven days). In the OT, seven-day mourning appears for Jacob (Gen 50:10), Saul (1 Sam 31:13), and as the Ezekiel mourning requirement (Ezek 3:15: Ezekiel sat among the exiles for seven days, overwhelmed). The silence of the friends during this period is remarkable: they observe Job&rsquo;s suffering, assess its severity as overwhelming, and choose presence-without-words over the premature comfort that would characterize all their subsequent speeches.</p>"
  },
  "3": {
    "1": "<p>Job&rsquo;s birthday curse in ch3 is closely paralleled in Jer 20:14&ndash;18, where Jeremiah curses the day of his birth in almost identical terms: &ldquo;Cursed be the day on which I was born! The day when my mother bore me, let it not be blessed!&rdquo; (Jer 20:14). The parallel is so close that scholars have debated literary dependence in one direction or another; most conclude that both texts draw on a common <strong>lament genre</strong> that included the birthday curse as an extreme expression of the death-wish. The genre served as a recognized, socially legitimate form for expressing suffering that had exceeded the capacity for endurance.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The formal introduction (<em>vaya&rsquo;an &rsquo;iyyov vayyomar</em>) marks the transition from the prose prologue to the poetic dialogue. Ancient Near Eastern wisdom literature frequently used prose frames for poetic wisdom dialogues: the <em>Ludlul bel nemeqi</em> opens and closes with prose, enclosing a poetic suffering-and-restoration narrative; the <em>Babylonian Theodicy</em> is entirely poetic; the Egyptian <em>Dialogue of a Man Who Contemplates Suicide with His Soul (Ba)</em> uses a similar frame. Job&rsquo;s opening speech initiates a formal literary mode distinct from the prologue.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The birthday curse inverts the birth announcement (&ldquo;a boy has been conceived!&rdquo;) &mdash; the joyful announcement of a son&rsquo;s birth that would have been celebrated by the household. In the ancient world, sons were the primary form of social security and continuation of the family line; the announcement of a son&rsquo;s birth was occasion for celebration (cf. Gen 21:6; Jer 20:15 where the man who announced Jeremiah&rsquo;s birth is cursed). Job wishes the announcement had never been made.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The inversion of the creation light (&ldquo;let that day be darkness; may God above not care for it&rdquo;) deliberately reverses Gen 1:3&ndash;4 (<em>yehi &rsquo;or</em>, let there be light). The six-day creation pattern begins with light; Job&rsquo;s anti-creation poem begins with the withdrawal of light. Ancient cosmologies understood darkness and light as cosmic principles in tension (the Enuma Elish describes the pre-creation state as darkness before the divine activity of ordering); Job&rsquo;s birthday curse calls for a reversal of the cosmic ordering that brought his day into being.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The call for darkness (<em>hoshekh</em>) and deep shadow (<em>tsalmavet</em>) to &ldquo;redeem&rdquo; (using <em>ga&rsquo;al</em>) the birthday uses the kinsman-redeemer legal institution ironically. The <em>go&rsquo;el</em> was the family member who redeemed enslaved relatives or repurchased ancestral property (Lev 25:25; Ruth 3:13; Jer 32:7). Job prays that darkness would perform the role of <em>go&rsquo;el</em> for his birthday &mdash; buying it back from the light, returning it to pre-creation chaos. The grotesque inversion of the redemption-concept reflects the extremity of Job&rsquo;s despair.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The wish that the night of his conception be excluded from the calendar (&ldquo;let it not be counted among the days of the year&rdquo;) reflects the ancient calendar&rsquo;s ritual significance. Ancient Near Eastern calendars were not simply practical counting systems; they were sacred structures within which divine activity was organized and celebrated. The feasts and new moons were not arbitrary divisions but divinely appointed times (<em>mo&rsquo;adim</em>). To be excluded from the calendar was to be excluded from the sacred structure of time itself.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The wish that the night be &ldquo;barren&rdquo; (<em>galmud</em>) uses a word associated with infertile women (Isa 49:21). Barrenness in the ancient world was one of the most severe social and personal stigmas, understood as divine disfavor (cf. the barren matriarchs: Sarah, Rebekah, Rachel, Hannah). Job wishes that the night of his birth had had the quality of infertility &mdash; unable to produce the child who is now suffering. The wish inverts the creation mandate to &ldquo;be fruitful and multiply.&rdquo;</p>",
    "8": "<p>The reference to <strong>professional cursers who know how to rouse Leviathan</strong> places Job&rsquo;s lament in a mythological register. <strong>Leviathan</strong> appears in Ugaritic texts as <em>Lotan</em>, the seven-headed sea monster who is defeated by Baal in the Baal-and-Yam cycle. Isaiah 27:1 describes YHWH slaying &ldquo;Leviathan the fleeing serpent, Leviathan the twisting serpent.&rdquo; In ancient Near Eastern cosmology, the chaos monster represented the primordial threat to created order; to &ldquo;rouse Leviathan&rdquo; would be to unleash cosmic chaos. Professional cursers who could activate such forces were part of the specialist-magic world of the ancient Near East (cf. Mesopotamian <em>mashmashu</em> exorcists and curse specialists).</p>",
    "9": "<p>The astronomical imagery &mdash; the stars of the predawn twilight (<em>kokhevei nishefo</em>), the expectation of light that does not come, the &ldquo;eyelids of the dawn&rdquo; (<em>&rsquo;apappei shahar</em>) &mdash; reflects the careful observation of the night sky characteristic of ancient Near Eastern astronomy. The Babylonians were the ancient world&rsquo;s most sophisticated astronomers; the stars and their movements were understood as divine signs (cf. the Mesopotamian omen literature). Job calls on the night to be deprived of its stars &mdash; its divine lights &mdash; and to experience perpetual darkness.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The womb-door (<em>daltei bitni</em>) image for birth reflects the ancient understanding of the womb as a guarded enclosure: the &ldquo;doors&rdquo; of the womb opening and closing correspond to the birth process. This anatomical metaphor is attested in various ancient medical and poetic texts. The wish that the womb-doors had remained closed expresses the death-wish in physiological terms: not death after birth, but non-existence through non-birth. Job&rsquo;s curse is not suicidal (he does not want to die now) but a wish for non-existence from the beginning.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The repeated <em>lama</em> (why) questions of Job 3 (vv11, 20, 23) are the quintessential lament interrogative. The <strong>lament genre</strong> in the Psalter (Pss 6, 13, 22, 44, 74, 79, 80, 88) regularly uses <em>lama</em> as the protest-cry: &ldquo;Why, O LORD, do you stand far off?&rdquo; (Ps 10:1); &ldquo;Why have you forgotten me?&rdquo; (Ps 42:9). The lament genre was a recognized, institutionally legitimate form of address to the deity: it did not expect a logical answer so much as it insisted that the deity hear and be moved. Job&rsquo;s <em>lama</em> operates in this tradition &mdash; a protest, not an inquiry.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The knees that received the newborn and the breasts that nursed are described in the context of the birth acceptance ritual. In the ancient world, a father receiving an infant on his knees was a gesture of formal acknowledgment of the child as his own (cf. Gen 50:23 where Joseph&rsquo;s grandchildren were placed on his knees). Without this acceptance, a child might be exposed. Job regrets that he was accepted at birth rather than exposed &mdash; a deeply ironic inversion of the normal birth-wish.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Job&rsquo;s description of Sheol as a place of rest (<em>nah</em>, <em>shaqat</em>, <em>shakav</em>, <em>yanuah</em>) is characteristic of the OT&rsquo;s generally subdued picture of the afterlife. Unlike Mesopotamian descriptions of the underworld (<em>Erkalla</em>), which included torment, dust, darkness, and misery (cf. the <em>Descent of Ishtar to the Underworld</em> and the <em>Gilgamesh</em> Enkidu underworld vision), the OT generally presents Sheol as a place of silence and rest &mdash; not happiness, but an end to suffering. Job finds this neutral cessation attractive in comparison with his present agony.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The kings and counselors who &ldquo;built ruins for themselves&rdquo; (or &ldquo;built desolate places&rdquo; / &ldquo;rebuilt ruins&rdquo;) are figures whose great achievements are now reduced to rubble. The phrase may refer to the rulers who built great monuments that have become ruins &mdash; the vanity of monumental building. In Ecclesiastes&rsquo; philosophical vocabulary (Eccl 2:4&ndash;11), the great building projects of the king become meaningless. The tomb-builders of Egypt were the epitome of this type: the pharaohs built enormous monuments to ensure post-death existence, yet they lie in the same silence as the poorest peasant.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The princes who &ldquo;filled their mansions with silver&rdquo; represent the accumulated wealth of the ancient aristocracy. Hoarding of silver and gold in palaces and temples was a standard practice in the ancient Near East (cf. the temple treasuries of Mesopotamia and Egypt); the vast wealth held in temples and royal treasuries is attested in countless administrative documents from Mesopotamia. In Sheol, all this accumulation is irrelevant: the wealthy and the poor are equally silent.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The stillborn (<em>nefel</em>) in the ancient world was typically buried quickly and without ceremony, often without a name, in an unmarked location. The stillborn had no social existence &mdash; was, as Job says, &ldquo;hidden away&rdquo; (<em>tamun</em>). Job envies this non-existence: the stillborn never experienced the suffering of life. Eccl 6:3&ndash;5 uses the stillborn as a similar philosophical benchmark: a man who lives many years but finds no satisfaction is worse off than a stillborn.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The picture of the wicked ceasing from their <em>rogez</em> (turmoil/agitation) in Sheol reflects the OT&rsquo;s understanding that social relationships and their associated conflicts simply end in death. The Mesopotamian picture of the underworld in the <em>Gilgamesh</em> epic includes former rulers and priests who are now all equally silent. The OT picture similarly levels all social distinctions: the taskmaster (<em>nogesh</em>) who drove slaves cannot drive them in Sheol.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Prisoners (<em>&rsquo;asirim</em>) resting together, no longer hearing the taskmaster&rsquo;s voice, evokes the Egyptian and Mesopotamian slave-labor contexts. In both Egypt (as described in Exodus) and Mesopotamia (where temple and royal building projects used corvée labor), <em>nagasim</em> (taskmasters/overseers) drove workers by voice command. The death that silences the taskmaster&rsquo;s voice is, for the prisoner, liberation. This is the most socially radical statement in Job&rsquo;s lament: even forced laborers find peace in death that they could not find in life.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The social leveling of Sheol &mdash; &ldquo;the lowly and the great are alike there, and the slave is free from his master&rdquo; &mdash; is a statement of radical equality that cuts against the social hierarchies of the ancient world. In Mesopotamia and Egypt, social rank was carefully maintained even in death (the afterlife of the Egyptian aristocracy required elaborate ritual preservation; ordinary people had minimal afterlife ritual). The OT&rsquo;s Sheol makes no such distinction. The statement that the slave (<em>&rsquo;eved</em>) is free (<em>hofshi</em>) from his master is among the OT&rsquo;s most subversive statements about the social order.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The &ldquo;one who labors under burden&rdquo; (<em>la&rsquo;amel</em>) is Job&rsquo;s self-description in the context of his rhetorical question: why give life to those who suffer? In the ancient world, the problem of innocent suffering was addressed by various traditions. The <em>Babylonian Theodicy</em> includes a dialogue where a sufferer notes that the gods favor the wicked over the righteous; the <em>Ludlul bel nemeqi</em> describes a nobleman abandoned by his divine protectors without explanation. These texts probe the same question as Job 3:20 from the Mesopotamian wisdom perspective: why does the suffering one continue to live?</p>",
    "21": "<p>The image of digging for death &ldquo;more eagerly than for buried treasure&rdquo; anticipates the mining imagery of ch28 (where wisdom is sought like hidden treasure). The comparison to mining/treasure-hunting for something longed-for is a literary thread connecting the death-wish of ch3 to the wisdom-search of ch28: in ch3, the thing longed for and sought eagerly is death; in ch28, the thing sought with similar intensity is wisdom; and the conclusion of ch28 is that neither death (Sheol/Abaddon) nor any human searching can find wisdom &mdash; only the fear of YHWH leads there.</p>",
    "22": "<p>That the dying person would &ldquo;exult and rejoice&rdquo; (<em>yagilu yishesu</em>) at reaching the grave expresses the death-wish at its most extreme. In the ancient world, the Stoic philosophers (centuries after Job) also addressed the question of whether suicide might be a rational response to extreme suffering. Plato&rsquo;s <em>Phaedo</em> includes a sustained treatment of the question. Job&rsquo;s lament raises the question in experiential rather than philosophical terms: the suffering is so extreme that death becomes desirable, not as oblivion, but as relief.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The image of God having &ldquo;fenced in&rdquo; (<em>yasek</em>) the suffering man echoes the adversary&rsquo;s use of the same vocabulary in 1:10 (God has &ldquo;fenced in&rdquo; Job as protection). The same enclosure that the adversary cited as the evidence of divine favor now appears from Job&rsquo;s internal experience as an entrapment &mdash; a fence that prevents escape. This is the book&rsquo;s first major verbal echo between the divine-court perspective (where the fence = divine protection) and the human experiential perspective (where the same fence = divine restriction).</p>",
    "24": "<p>Job&rsquo;s description of his groaning coming before his food (<em>ki lifne-lahmi &rsquo;anhati tavo</em>) reflects the physical reality of grief: intense grief disrupts the appetite (cf. Hannah&rsquo;s refusal to eat in 1 Sam 1:7; David&rsquo;s fasting during the illness of his child in 2 Sam 12:16&ndash;23). In the ancient world, grief was not merely psychological but physical; the lament texts of Mesopotamia and the biblical Psalms frequently describe the physical dimensions of suffering (Ps 22:14&ndash;17; Ps 102:3&ndash;7).</p>",
    "25": "<p>Job&rsquo;s statement that &ldquo;what I most dreaded has happened to me&rdquo; has generated theological debate: was Job&rsquo;s dread a moral failure, suggesting insufficient trust in YHWH? The context of the lament genre argues against this reading &mdash; the expression is a way of saying that the worst imaginable outcome has occurred. The genre of lament regularly describes the speaker&rsquo;s extremity rather than their moral deficiency. In Ps 22, the speaker describes being abandoned by God without this implying a specific moral failure.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The three negated nouns of rest &mdash; <em>shalav</em> (ease), <em>shaqat</em> (quiet), <em>nuah</em> (settled rest) &mdash; and the arrival of <em>rogez</em> (agitation/turmoil) form a perfect inversion of Job&rsquo;s former life as described in ch29 (where he was surrounded by abundance and stability). The word <em>rogez</em> here (agitation, turmoil) is the same word used in 3:17 for what the wicked cease from in Sheol. Job&rsquo;s living experience is thus the opposite of Sheol&rsquo;s rest: he has the <em>rogez</em> that stops only in death, while the wicked find rest he cannot access in life.</p>"
  },
  "4": {
    "1": "<p>Eliphaz&rsquo;s first speech is widely considered the theologically most sophisticated of the three friends&rsquo; contributions. His geographical origin &mdash; <strong>Teman</strong> &mdash; marks him as a representative of the Edomite wisdom tradition. Teman (modern Tawilan, near Petra, Jordan) was the capital region of Edom; Jer 49:7 and Obad 1:8 both identify Teman with wisdom: &ldquo;Is wisdom no more in Teman? Has counsel perished from the prudent?&rdquo; The book of Job thus presents its most sophisticated theological opponent as the heir of the most renowned non-Israelite wisdom tradition.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Eliphaz begins with an elaborate apology for speaking, acknowledging the sensitivity of Job&rsquo;s situation. In ancient wisdom discourse, this kind of hedge (&ldquo;if one ventures a word with you, will it trouble you?&rdquo;) was a standard rhetorical opener that demonstrated social awareness before delivering a potentially unwelcome message. Egyptian wisdom texts like the <em>Instructions of Amenemope</em> and <em>Ptahhotep</em> include similar hedging formulae before delivering hard wisdom. The <em>aposiopesis</em> (the self-interruption of the inner compulsion to speak overriding the social caution) was also a recognized rhetorical move.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Eliphaz&rsquo;s acknowledgment of Job&rsquo;s past role as a strengthener and teacher of others (<em>yissarta rabbim</em>, you have instructed many) is a recognition of Job&rsquo;s social position as a wisdom teacher. In the ancient world, the sage who could provide counsel in distress was a valued social resource. Prov 31:26 describes the capable woman: &ldquo;she opens her mouth in wisdom; the teaching of kindness is on her tongue.&rdquo; Eliphaz is acknowledging that Job has played this exact role for others &mdash; which is precisely why his inability to apply his own counsel to himself is, in Eliphaz&rsquo;s view, so striking.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The imagery of &ldquo;stumbling ones&rdquo; (<em>mikhshol</em>) being steadied and &ldquo;buckling knees&rdquo; (<em>birkhayim kor&rsquo;ot</em>) being strengthened comes from the vocabulary of the wisdom teacher&rsquo;s pastoral function. Isa 35:3 uses the same double image (&ldquo;strengthen the weak hands and make firm the feeble knees&rdquo;) in the context of eschatological encouragement. The pastoral function of wisdom &mdash; steadying the troubled, strengthening the despairing &mdash; was a recognized social role in the ancient world. Eliphaz is effectively saying: &ldquo;you were a wisdom teacher; where is that wisdom now?&rdquo;</p>",
    "5": "<p>The before-and-after contrast (<em>&rsquo;atah</em> = now) is Eliphaz&rsquo;s most pointed observation: Job counseled others effectively but cannot bear his own counsel when suffering touches him personally. The word translated &ldquo;impatient&rdquo; (<em>tila&rsquo;eh</em>) comes from a root meaning to be weary, exhausted, worn out. This is not a moral condemnation but an observation about the gap between theoretical wisdom and embodied experience of suffering &mdash; a gap that remains a perpetual challenge in the wisdom traditions of every culture.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Eliphaz&rsquo;s appeal to Job&rsquo;s own piety as the source of his confidence (<em>&rsquo;yir&rsquo;atekha kislat&rsquo;kha</em>, your fear of God is your confidence) is the friends&rsquo; most reasonable argument. In the Psalter, the God-fearer&rsquo;s confidence is precisely that YHWH protects the righteous (Ps 34:7; 91:1&ndash;4). The wisdom tradition consistently taught that the fear of YHWH was the foundation of security (Prov 14:26: &ldquo;in the fear of YHWH one has strong confidence&rdquo;). Eliphaz is not being gratuitously cruel; he is applying the received wisdom tradition to Job&rsquo;s situation. The problem is that this tradition does not account for the book&rsquo;s actual situation.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The retributive justice axiom &mdash; no innocent person perishes; no upright person is cut off &mdash; is the foundational moral claim of the friends and is deeply embedded in both OT Deuteronomic theology (Deut 28: blessings for obedience, curses for disobedience) and in ancient Near Eastern wisdom. The <em>Babylonian Theodicy</em> (ca. 1000 BCE) includes a parallel claim that suffering indicates sin; the <em>Instructions of Amenemope</em> and many Mesopotamian wisdom texts operate within the retributive-justice framework. The book of Job&rsquo;s distinctive contribution to the wisdom tradition is its sustained challenge to this axiom through the case of undeniable innocent suffering.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The agricultural metaphor &mdash; plowing (<em>harash</em>) iniquity, sowing (<em>zara&rsquo;</em>) trouble, reaping the same &mdash; reflects the agricultural world of the ancient Near East where sowing and reaping governed all understanding of causation. The metaphor appears throughout the OT (Hos 8:7: &ldquo;they sow the wind and reap the whirlwind&rdquo;; Prov 22:8: &ldquo;whoever sows injustice will reap calamity&rdquo;; Gal 6:7 in the NT). The agricultural law of causation (you reap what you sow) is universally intuitive and deeply embedded in all agricultural civilizations&rsquo; moral reasoning.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The breath of God (<em>nismat &rsquo;el</em>) and the blast of his nostrils (<em>ruah &rsquo;apo</em>) destroying the wicked reflects the storm-god imagery of the ancient Near East. In Ugaritic mythology, Baal&rsquo;s power was expressed through storms and lightning; in Mesopotamian theology, Enlil&rsquo;s breath (the wind) had cosmic destructive power. The OT consistently uses storm imagery for divine judgment (Ps 18:15&ndash;16; Isa 30:28; Nah 1:3). Eliphaz&rsquo;s argument: the same divine breath that sustains the righteous (Gen 2:7) destroys the wicked.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The lion imagery (v10&ndash;11) is among the most common metaphors in ancient Near Eastern wisdom literature for the powerful who are eventually brought low. Lions appear in Mesopotamian royal imagery as symbols of royal power (Assyrian kings hunted lions as a display of dominance); in Ugaritic texts, the lion is associated with the warrior-goddess Anat. In the OT, lions serve as metaphors for both the wicked powerful (Prov 28:15; Ezek 22:25) and for divine power (Isa 31:4; Hos 5:14). Eliphaz&rsquo;s use of the lion metaphor implies that even the most powerful wicked are ultimately destroyed.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The four lion-words in vv10&ndash;11 &mdash; <em>&rsquo;aryeh</em> (the generic lion), <em>shahats</em> (the fierce lion, perhaps a lioness), <em>benei kefir</em> (young lions), and <em>layish</em> (the mature/experienced lion) &mdash; reflect the precision of ancient vocabulary for a dangerous predator. The Ugaritic texts similarly distinguish multiple lion-types. The use of four lion-words in two verses is a display of the extensive vocabulary available to an educated ANE sage on the topic of predatory power and its limits.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Eliphaz&rsquo;s claim of a nocturnal revelation raises the question of <strong>dream-incubation</strong> in the ancient world. In Mesopotamian practice, a person seeking divine communication could sleep in a temple (<em>bitu</em>) to receive a dream; in Egypt, the practice of <em>incubation</em> (sleeping at a sacred site to receive a divine dream) was widespread. The OT similarly recognizes nocturnal divine communication (Gen 28:12 Jacob&rsquo;s ladder; 1 Kgs 3:5 Solomon&rsquo;s dream). Eliphaz&rsquo;s revelation came unbidden, by stealth, as a faint whisper &mdash; which is consistent with the OT&rsquo;s preference for non-dramatic divine communication (1 Kgs 19:12: &ldquo;after the fire, a sound of sheer silence&rdquo;).</p>",
    "13": "<p>The deep sleep (<em>tardema</em>) in which divine revelation comes parallels the two other major uses of this word in the OT: Adam&rsquo;s deep sleep in Gen 2:21 (during which Eve is created) and Abraham&rsquo;s in Gen 15:12 (during which the covenant is enacted). In both cases, <em>tardema</em> precedes a divine act of creation or covenant. In the ancient world, the boundary between sleep and vision-trance was not sharply distinguished; both were recognized as states in which divine communication could occur. The Mesopotamian <em>baru</em> (diviner) literature discusses the various states of consciousness in which divine communication was received.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The physical effects of theophanic experience &mdash; fear, trembling, bone-shaking, bristling hair &mdash; are attested across the ancient world&rsquo;s religious literature. In Mesopotamian texts, the experience of divine presence caused <em>puluhtu</em> (terror/awe) and physical symptoms including hair standing on end. The OT similarly describes the physical effects of divine encounter: Isaiah in the throne-room vision cries out &ldquo;Woe is me!&rdquo; (Isa 6:5); Daniel falls on his face (Dan 10:9). The hair-bristling response (<em>yisammer se&rsquo;ar besari</em>) is the same as what modern physiology calls piloerection (goosebumps) &mdash; the universal human response to intense fear or awe.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The spirit (<em>ruah</em>) passing before Eliphaz&rsquo;s face uses a theophanic category familiar from the OT: the divine presence &ldquo;passes before&rdquo; as a manifestation of power (Exod 33:19&ndash;22: YHWH&rsquo;s glory passes before Moses; 1 Kgs 19:11: &ldquo;a great and strong wind&rdquo; passes before Elijah). In the ancient world, wind/breath was understood as the most common form of invisible divine presence &mdash; the breath of the god that could be felt but not seen. Eliphaz&rsquo;s description of a <em>ruah</em> passing his face, causing physical manifestations, places his experience in the category of genuine theophanic encounter.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The apparition&rsquo;s standing still without visible form (<em>temunah</em>) followed by a voice distinguishes Eliphaz&rsquo;s experience from Moses&rsquo;s unique encounter at Sinai (Num 12:8: YHWH speaks to Moses &ldquo;mouth to mouth&rdquo; and Moses sees the <em>temunah</em> of YHWH). Deut 4:12 uses the same distinction to describe the Sinai encounter: &ldquo;you heard the sound of words but saw no form (<em>temunah</em>).&rdquo; Eliphaz received a voice-only revelation, without form &mdash; placed below Moses&rsquo;s level but within the recognized range of genuine divine communication.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The rhetorical question &mdash; can a <em>&rsquo;enosh</em> (mortal human) be more righteous than God? &mdash; is the friends&rsquo; theological centerpiece. The Mesopotamian wisdom text <em>Ludlul bel nemeqi</em> includes the line: &ldquo;Who knows the will of the gods in heaven? Who understands the plans of the underworld gods?&rdquo; &mdash; emphasizing the incomprehensibility of divine decisions. The Egyptian <em>Maxims of Ptahhotep</em> counsel submission to the divine order as the foundation of wisdom. All ancient wisdom traditions share the baseline assumption that human beings cannot critique or surpass the gods; Eliphaz&rsquo;s question is in this tradition.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The theological argument from divine standards &mdash; if God does not trust his servants or his angels, how much less can mortals be trusted &mdash; reflects a well-known argument pattern in ancient legal and wisdom thought (the <em>qal vahomer</em>, &ldquo;light and heavy,&rdquo; argument: if X is true in the less serious case, how much more in the more serious case). The concept of angels (<em>mal&rsquo;akhim</em>) as divine servants who can make errors reflects an OT tradition in which the divine council members are fallible (Ps 82: God judges the &ldquo;gods&rdquo; who have failed in their judicial responsibilities).</p>",
    "19": "<p>The image of humans as <em>batei homer</em> (houses of clay) is closely paralleled in Mesopotamian creation texts. The <em>Atrahasis</em> epic describes human creation from clay mixed with divine blood; the <em>Enuma Elish</em> describes humans made from clay to do the work of the gods. The OT uses the same imagery: Gen 2:7 (<em>afar min-ha&rsquo;adamah</em>, dust from the ground), Isa 64:8 (we are the clay, YHWH is the potter), Ps 103:14 (he knows that we are dust). Eliphaz draws on a cosmological assumption shared by the entire ancient world: humans are clay-creatures whose fundamental fragility is inscribed in their very constitution.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The observation that human life ends so quickly &mdash; &ldquo;between morning and evening they are destroyed; without anyone noticing, they vanish forever&rdquo; &mdash; reflects the ancient world&rsquo;s acute consciousness of human transience. Ps 90:3&ndash;6 (attributed to Moses) uses similar imagery: humans are swept away &ldquo;like a dream, like grass that is renewed in the morning.&rdquo; Egyptian funerary literature extensively meditates on the brevity of human life. The observation that individual human deaths go unnoticed by the cosmos (&ldquo;without anyone noticing&rdquo;) is a philosophical observation characteristic of the post-Bronze-Age wisdom traditions&rsquo; more naturalistic view of death.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The final image of the tent-peg (<em>yeter</em>) pulled up from within &mdash; leaving the tent without structural support, destined to collapse &mdash; uses a metaphor from the nomadic world of the ancient Near East where tents were the standard dwelling. The tent-peg that anchors the tent from the inside is the central structural element; when it is removed, the entire structure collapses. Paul uses the same tent metaphor in 2 Cor 5:1 (&ldquo;if the earthly tent we live in is destroyed&rdquo;). Eliphaz&rsquo;s conclusion: mortals die before attaining wisdom (<em>bemah hokhmah</em>), making any human claim to righteousness before God epistemically groundless.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'job')
    merge_comm(existing, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'job', existing)
    total = sum(len(vv) for vv in CONTEXT.values())
    print(f'Job 1-4 mkt-context: {total} verses written '
          '(' + ', '.join(f'ch{ch}={len(CONTEXT[ch])}' for ch in sorted(CONTEXT)) + ').')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
